He also lays bare the criminal justice system’s internal political pressures. How does the fact that judges, sheriffs, and prosecutors are elected officials influence how they view cases? How can defense attorneys support clients when many are overworked and underpaid? And how do juries overcome bias leading them to believe that police and expert witnesses know more than they do about what evidence means? This book sheds a harsh light on the unintentional yet routine injustices committed by those charged with upholding justice. Yet in the end, Godsey recommends structural, procedural, and attitudinal changes aimed at restoring justice to the criminal justice system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 0aEvidence, CriminalzUnited States. 0aFalse imprisonmentzUnited States. 0aJudicial errorzUnited States. 0aPrejudiceszUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 0aPrejudiceszUnited States.xPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aamerican judicial system.  abureaucracy.  adehumanization.  ahuman weakness.  ainnocent imprisoned.  alawyers.  aohio innocence project.  apenitentiary workers.  apsychologists.  apsychology.  asocial justice.  atough on crime.  awrongful convictions.  awrongfully convicted.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028795240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096295840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962958423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962958/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  Univer